","1375–1425":"1375–1425","1388–Male":"1388–Overleden","1390–Male":"1390–Overleden","1318–Male":"1318–Overleden","1322–Female":"1322–Overleden","1425":"1425","about 1390":"circa 1390","1358":"1358","1322":"1322","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","about 1375":"circa 1375","1318":"1318","1390":"1390","abt 1388":"circa 1388","Boycott Township, Pontesbury, Shropshire, England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England","England":"England","Pontesbury, Shropshire, England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1354–":"1354–Deceased","1352–Male":"1352–Deceased","1354–Male":"1354–Deceased","1358–Female":"1358–Deceased","1375–1425":"1375–1425","1388–Male":"1388–Deceased","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1318–Male":"1318–Deceased","1322–Female":"1322–Deceased","1425":"1425","about 1390":"about 1390","1358":"1358","1322":"1322","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","about 1375":"about 1375","1318":"1318","1390":"1390","abt 1388":"about 1388","Boycott Township, Pontesbury, Shropshire, England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England","England":"England","Pontesbury, Shropshire, England":"Pontesbury, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Higgins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hUiginn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Uiginn</i>’, a byname meaning ‘viking, sea-rover’ (from Old Norse <i>víkingr</i>). Compare   McGuigan  .","English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of <b>Higgin</b>, itself either a Lancashire variant of <b>Huggin</b> (from a pet form of   Hugh  ), or a variant of   Hickin   (from a pet form of   Richard  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. See   Hick   and compare   Higson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Higgens","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Higgins  ."]},{"name":"McGuigan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam, Mairead.","Irish (northern): perhaps an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Uiginn</b> ‘son of the viking’ (see   Higgins   1).","Irish (northern): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Guagáin</b>, a shortened form of <b>Mag Eochagáin</b>, son of <i>Eochagán</i>, a diminutive of <i>Eochaidh</i> ‘horseman’. Compare   Geoghegan  ."]},{"name":"Haggins","meanings":["Scottish variant of Irish   Higgins  ."]},{"name":"Heggins","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Higgins   1."]},{"name":"Kiggins","meanings":["Irish (Galway and Mayo) and Manx: shortened Anglicized form (with English excrescent <i>-s</i>) of Gaelic <b>Mag Uiginn</b> ‘son of the Viking’ (see   Higgins  )."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Higgins was born in 1354, his father, Richard Higgins, was 37 and his mother, Joan de Bowdler, was 33. He had at least 3 sons with Matilda Saisach."},"et":{"1354–":"1354–Surnud","1352–Male":"1352–Surnud","1354–Male":"1354–Surnud","1358–Female":"1358–Surnud","1375–1425":"1375–1425","1388–Male":"1388–Surnud","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1318–Male":"1318–Surnud","1322–Female":"1322–Surnud","1425":"1425","about 1390